# Telco CRM — Security Architecture

## JWT Authentication Flow

- `identity-service` is the **sole issuer** of JWT access and refresh tokens (jjwt `0.12.6`).
- `api-gateway` validates every inbound JWT and, on success, injects `X-User-Id` and `X-User-Roles` headers into the downstream request.
- **Microservices must never validate the JWT themselves.** They trust the gateway-injected headers.
- Do not add `spring-boot-starter-security` + JWT parsing to any service other than `identity-service` and `api-gateway`.

```java
// ✅ GOOD — microservice reads identity from header only
String userId = request.getHeader("X-User-Id");

// ❌ BAD — microservice re-parses the JWT
String userId = jwtUtil.extractUserId(request.getHeader("Authorization"));
```

## Authorization

- Use `@PreAuthorize` for all endpoint-level access control. Never implement manual role checks inside service methods.
- Admin-only endpoints (e.g., billing run trigger, product catalog mutation) must always carry an explicit `@PreAuthorize` annotation.

```java
// ✅ GOOD
@PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
@PostMapping("/billing/runs")
public ResponseEntity<Void> triggerBillRun() { ... }
```

## Refresh Token Rotation

- After every successful token refresh, add the consumed refresh token to a Redis blacklist.
- On any reuse of a blacklisted refresh token, immediately revoke **all** active tokens for that user.
- Never store refresh tokens in the database; use Redis with an appropriate TTL.

## PII Encryption

- The following fields are PII and **must be stored encrypted** using AES-GCM:
  - `Customer.identityNumber` (TCKN / VKN)
  - `Payment.cardNumber` (and any card-related field)
- Encryption keys must be read from Vault or Kubernetes Secrets. Never hardcode or commit keys.
- Decryption must only happen at the service layer; raw encrypted bytes must never leak into API responses.

```java
// ✅ GOOD
@Column(name = "identity_number")
private String identityNumber; // stored as AES-GCM ciphertext, decrypted in service layer

// ❌ BAD — returning raw PII from repository to controller without decryption guard
```

## Audit Logging

The following services must write an `audit_log` record on **every state-mutating operation** (create, update, delete, status change):
- `identity-service`
- `customer-service`
- `payment-service`
- `subscription-service`

Minimum audit log fields: `entityType`, `entityId`, `action`, `performedBy` (userId), `performedAt` (UTC timestamp), `before` (JSON snapshot), `after` (JSON snapshot).

## Rate Limiting

- Rate limiting is enforced at the `api-gateway` using Redis.
- Default limit: **100 requests/minute per authenticated user**.
- Do not implement additional rate limiting inside individual microservices for user traffic.

## KVKK / GDPR Compliance

- Never hard-delete `Customer` records. Always use soft delete (set `deletedAt` timestamp).
- PII fields must be included in the data retention and erasure process; use field-level encryption to enable cryptographic erasure.
- Audit logs for customer data changes are mandatory to satisfy KVKK regulatory requirements.
